{
  "abstract": "One of the possibilities for increasing the yield\r\nof groundnut , particularly in the Semi -Arid\r\nTropics, is breeding varieties wi th resistance to\r\npests and diseases. Some progress has been\r\nmade in this field, but the improvements that\r\ncan be made by breeders are limited by the\r\navailability of genes wi thin A. hypogaea. Collect\r\nions of wild species from South America have\r\nmade available a wider range of genes, especially\r\ngenes for disease resistance. The richness\r\nof Arachis germplasm collection offers a great\r\nopportunity for anyone interested in the improvement\r\nof this crop (Bunting et al. 1974, Simpson 1976; Smartt et a I. 1978a, b; Gregory\r\nand Gregory 1979).",
